{"id":"2001.08137","submitter":"Mar\\'ia Jos\\'e Guzm\\'an","authors":"Rafael Ferraro and Mar\\'ia Jos\\'e Guzm\\'an","title":"Pseudoinvariance and the extra degree of freedom in f(T) gravity","comments":"22 pages, 2 tables, no figures, comments welcome; matches the\n  published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 101, 084017 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.101.084017","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc physics.class-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Nonlinear generalizations of teleparallel gravity entail the modification of\na Lagrangian that is pseudoinvariant under local Lorentz transformations of the\ntetrad field. This procedure consequently leads to the loss of the local\npseudoinvariance and the appearance of additional degrees of freedom (d.o.f.).\nThe constraint structure of f(T) gravity suggests the existence of one extra\nd.o.f. when compared with GR, which should describe some aspect of the\norientation of the tetrad. The purpose of this article is to better understand\nthe nature of this extra d.o.f. by means of a toy model that mimics essential\nfeatures of f(T) gravity. We find that the nonlinear modification of a\nLagrangian L possessing a local rotational pseudoinvariance produces two types\nof solutions. In one case the original gauge-invariant variables -- the\nanalogue of the metric in teleparallelism -- evolve like when governed by the\n(nondeformed) Lagrangian L; these solutions are characterized by a (selectable)\nconstant value of its Lagrangian, which is the manifestation of the extra\nd.o.f. In the other case, the solutions do contain new dynamics for the\noriginal gauge-invariant variables, but the extra d.o.f. does not materialize\nbecause the Lagrangian remains invariant on-shell. Coming back to f(T) gravity,\nthe first case includes solutions where the torsion scalar T is a constant, to\nbe chosen at the initial conditions (extra d.o.f.), and no new dynamics for the\nmetric is expected. 